title: ApplyKlass
description: Apply a classification to a variable/vector.
contents:
Contents
1. Retrieving classification name
2. Language
3. Change level
4. More help

ApplyKlass is designed to provide an easy interface to applying classifications from Statistic Norway’s classification database. It can be used on a vector.
See https://www.ssb.no/klass/ for details on Statistic Norway’s classifications and codelist.



1. Retrieving classification name
ApplyKlass can be used to retreive the name of a classification vector.


library(klassR)
dt <- data.frame(orgnr = c(324833,95765, 32732),
                 naering = c("01", "05", "06"))
dt$naering_name <- ApplyKlass(dt$naering, klass = 6)
dt




orgnr
naering
naering_name
324833
01
Jordbruk og tjenester tilknyttet jordbruk, jakt og viltstell
95765
05
Bryting av steinkull og brunkull
32732
06
Utvinning av råolje og naturgass

2. Language
Different languages can be fetched out. These are coded “nn” for nynorsk, “nb” for bokmål and “en” for English.


dt$naering_name <- ApplyKlass(dt$naering, klass = 6, language = "en")
dt




orgnr
naering
naering_name
324833
01
Crop and animal production, hunting and related service activities
95765
05
Mining of coal and lignite
32732
06
Extraction of crude petroleum and natural gas

3. Change level
Sometimes a different level is desired. In this case we specify using the output_level parameter.


dt$hoved_naering <- ApplyKlass(dt$naering, 
                               klass = 6,
                               output_level = 1,
                               output = "code")
dt




orgnr
naering
naering_name
hoved_naering
324833
01
Crop and animal production, hunting and related service activities
A
95765
05
Mining of coal and lignite
B
32732
06
Extraction of crude petroleum and natural gas
B

4. More help
See https://www.ssb.no/klass/ for details on Statistic Norway’s classifications and codelist.

title: HierarchyCompute
description: This function computes aggregates by crossing several hierarchical specifications and factorial variables.
contents:
library(SSBtools)

# Data and hierarchies used in the examples
x <- SSBtoolsData("sprt_emp") # Employment in sport in thousand persons from Eurostat database
geoHier <- SSBtoolsData("sprt_emp_geoHier")
ageHier <- SSBtoolsData("sprt_emp_ageHier")
# Two hierarchies and year as rowFactor
HierarchyCompute(x, list(age = ageHier, geo = geoHier, year = "rowFactor"), "ths_per")


     age    geo year ths_per
1 Y15-64 Europe 2014   222.3
2 Y15-64  nonEU 2014     3.3
3 Y15-64     EU 2014   219.0
4 Y15-64 Europe 2015   225.0
5 Y15-64  nonEU 2015     3.5
6 Y15-64     EU 2015   221.5
7 Y15-64 Europe 2016   233.5
8 Y15-64  nonEU 2016     3.8
9 Y15-64     EU 2016   229.7

title: CalibrateSSB
description: Functions to calculate weights, estimates of changes and corresponding variance estimates for panel data with non-response. Partially overlapping samples are handled. Initially, weights are calculated by linear calibration.
contents:
1. Examples of using CalibrateSSB


library(CalibrateSSB)

# Generates data - two years
z <- AkuData(3000) # 3000 in each quarter
zPop <- AkuData(10000)[,1:7]

# Calibration using "survey"
a <- CalibrateSSB(z, calmodel = "~ sex*age",
partition = c("year","q"), # calibrate within quarter
popData = zPop, y = c("unemployed","workforce"),
by = c("year","q")) # Estimate within quarter
head(a$w) # calibrated weights


[1] 3.837743 3.583979 3.757660 3.837743 3.676320 3.583979

a$estTM # estimates

a$popTotals # popTotals used as input below

# Calibration, no package, popTotals as input
b <- CalibrateSSB(z, popTotals=a$popTotals, 
                  calmodel="~ sex*age", 
                  partition = c("year","q"), 
                  usePackage = "none", 
                  y = c("unemployed","workforce"))
max(abs(a$w-b$w)) # Same weights as above

title: LmImpute
description: Imputation by weighted regeression, using lm, allowing multiple explanatory variables and multiple response variables. Impute missing and wrong values (category 3) by the model based on representative data (category 1). Some data are considered correct but not representative (category 2)

title: protectTable
description: Function protectTable() is used to protect primary sensitive table cells (that usually have been identified and set using primarySuppression()). The function protects primary sensitive table cells according to the method that has been chosen and the parameters that have been set.
